{"title_page": "Bobby Jones (golfer)", "text_new": "{{Use American English|date = December 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox golfer\n| name              = Bobby Jones\n| image             = Bobby Jones c1921.jpg\n| imagesize         = 230px\n| caption           = Jones, {{circa|1921}}\n| fullname          = Robert Tyre Jones Jr.\n| nickname          = \n| birth_date        = {{Birth date|1902|3|17|mf=y}}\n| birth_place       = [[Atlanta]], Georgia, U.S.\n| death_date        = {{Death date and age|1971|12|18|1902|3|17|mf=y}}\n| death_place       = Atlanta, Georgia, U.S.\n| height            = {{height|ft=5|in=8}}\n| weight            = {{convert|165|lb|kg st|abbr=on}}\n| nationality       = {{USA}}\n| spouse            = {{marriage|Mary Rice Malone<br>|1924}}\n| children          = 3\n| college           = [[Georgia Institute of Technology|Georgia Tech]]<br/>[[Harvard University]]<br/>[[Emory University]]\n| status            = Amateur\n| retired           = 1930\n| extour            = <!-- Former tours which a member of -->\n| prowins           = 9<ref>Jones was an amateur in his nine wins in professional tournaments.</ref>\n| pgawins           = 9\n| otherwins         =\n| majorwins         = 13\n| masters           = T13: 1934\n| usopen            = {{nowrap|'''Won''': [[1923 U.S. Open (golf)|1923]], [[1926 U.S. Open (golf)|1926]], [[1929 U.S. Open (golf)|1929]], [[1930 U.S. Open (golf)|1930]]}}\n| open              = '''Won''': [[1926 Open Championship|1926]], [[1927 Open Championship|1927]], [[1930 Open Championship|1930]]\n| pga               = DNP\n| usamateur         = '''Won''': 1924, 1925, 1927, 1928, 1930\n| britamateur       = '''Won''': 1930\n| wghofid           = bobby-jones\n| wghofyear         = 1974\n| award1            = [[James E. Sullivan Award]]\n| year1             = 1930\n| award2            = [[Georgia Tech Hall of Fame#Golf|Georgia Tech Athletic<br>Hall of Fame]]\n| year2             = 1958<ref name = \"tech\">{{cite web |url=http://livinghistory.gatech.edu/new/traditions/legend/jones.html |title=Bobby Jones |publisher=Georgia Tech |accessdate=August 21, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ramblinwreck.com/ot/fame/halloffame.html#gol |title=Georgia Tech Athletics Hall of Fame |publisher=ramblinwreck.com |accessdate=August 21, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006113939/http://www.ramblinwreck.com/ot/fame/halloffame.html#gol#gol |archive-date=October 6, 2014 |url-status=dead  }}</ref>\n| award3            = Georgia Tech Engineering<br>Hall of Fame\n| year3             = 1997<ref name = \"tech\"/>\n| awardssection     = <!-- location of awards page or section -->\n}}\n{{Infobox military person\n|allegiance    = {{USA}}\n|branch        = [[File:US Army Air Corps Hap Arnold Wings.svg|15px]] [[United States Army Air Corps|U.S. Army Air Corps]]\n|rank          = [[File:US-O5 insignia.svg|15px]] &nbsp;[[Lieutenant colonel (United States)|Lieutenant colonel]]\n|unit          = Intelligence\n|serviceyears  = <!--194x\u20131945-->\n|battles       = [[World War II]], [[European theatre of World War II|European theater]]\n|awards        = \n}}\n'''Robert Tyre Jones Jr.''' (March 17, 1902 \u2013 December 18, 1971) was an American amateur golfer who was one of the most influential figures in the history of the sport; he was also a lawyer by profession. Jones founded and helped design the [[Augusta National Golf Club]], and co-founded the [[Masters Tournament]]. The innovations that he introduced at the Masters have been copied by virtually every professional golf tournament in the world.\n\nJones was the most successful amateur golfer ever to compete at a national and international level. During his peak from 1923 to 1930, he dominated top-level amateur competition, and competed very successfully against the world's best professional golfers.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Hardin |first=Robin |title=Crowning the King: Grantland Rice and Bobby Jones |journal=Georgia Historical Quarterly |year=2004 |volume=88 |issue=4 |pages=511\u2013529 |url=http://search.ebscohost.com/login.aspx?direct=true&db=a9h&AN=15596790&site=eds-live&scope=site |accessdate=February 15, 2018}}</ref> Jones often beat stars such as [[Walter Hagen]] and [[Gene Sarazen]], the era's top pros. Jones earned his living mainly as a lawyer, and competed in golf only as an amateur, primarily on a part-time basis, and chose to retire from competition at age 28, though he earned significant money from golf after that, as an instructor and equipment designer.\n\nExplaining his decision to retire, Jones said, \"It [championship golf] is something like a cage. First you are expected to get into it and then you are expected to stay there. But of course, nobody can stay there.\"<ref>{{cite book |title=The Gigantic Book of Golf Quotations |editor-first=Jim |editor-last=Apfelbaum |year=2007 |publisher=Skyhorse Publishing |isbn=978-1-60239-014-0}}</ref> Jones is most famous for his unique \"[[Grand Slam (golf)|Grand Slam]],\" consisting of his victory in all four [[Men's major golf championships|major golf tournaments]] of his era (the open and amateur championships in both the U.S. & the U.K.) in a single calendar year (1930). In all Jones played in 31 majors, winning 13 and placing among the top ten finishers 27 times.\n\nAfter retiring from competitive golf in 1930, Jones founded and helped design the Augusta National Golf Club soon afterwards in 1933. He also co-founded the Masters Tournament, which has been annually staged by the club since [[1934 Masters Tournament|1934]] (except for 1943\u201345, when it was canceled due to [[World War II]]). The Masters evolved into one of golf's four major championships. Jones came out of retirement in 1934 to play in the Masters on an exhibition basis through [[1948 Masters Tournament|1948]]. Jones played his last round of golf at [[East Lake Golf Club]], his home course in Atlanta, on August 18, 1948. A picture commemorating the event now sits in the clubhouse at East Lake. Citing health reasons, he quit golf permanently thereafter.\n\nBobby Jones was often confused with the prolific golf course designer, [[Robert Trent Jones]], with whom he worked from time to time. \"People always used to get them confused, so when they met, they decided each be called something different,\" Robert Trent Jones Jr. said. To help avoid confusion, the golfer was called \"Bobby,\" and the golf course designer was called \"Trent.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/2000-06-16/sports/0006160238_1_golf-course-architecture-easy-bogey-robert-trent-jones |title=Course Designer Jones Dies |newspaper=[[Sun-Sentinel]] |accessdate=May 4, 2014 |first=Michael |last=Mayo |date=June 16, 2000}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\n===Early years===\n[[File:BobbyJonesAge14.jpg|left|120px|thumb|Jones at age 14]]\nBorn in [[Atlanta]], Georgia, Jones battled health issues as a young boy, and golf was prescribed to strengthen him. Encouraged by his father, \"Colonel\" Robert Purmedus Jones, an Atlanta lawyer, Jones loved golf from the start. He developed quickly into a child prodigy who won his first children's tournament at the age of six at his home course at [[East Lake Golf Club]].  In 1916, Jones won his first major golf event when he claimed the inaugural Georgia Amateur Championship conducted by the Georgia State Golf Association at the Capital City Club, in Brookhaven, at age 14.  His victory at this event put him in the national spotlight for the first time. The Georgia Amateur win caught the eye of the United States Golf Association which awarded Jones his first invitation to the [[U.S. Amateur]] at [[Merion Golf Club|Merion]] near [[Philadelphia]]. Jones advanced to the quarterfinals in his first playing in the event.<ref name = \"timeline\">{{cite web |url=http://www.bobbyjones.com/the-legend_historical-timeline/#callout-1955 |title=The Legend \u2013 Historical Timeline |publisher=bobbyjones.com |accessdate=August 28, 2013}}</ref>\n\nHe was influenced by club professional [[Stewart Maiden]], a native of [[Carnoustie]], Scotland. Maiden was the professional at the [[Atlanta Athletic Club]]'s [[East Lake Golf Club]], who also trained [[Alexa Stirling]], the 3-time winner of the [[U.S. Women's Amateur]], who was five years older than Jones but also a prodigy at East Lake.<ref name=barclay>{{cite book |title=Golf in Canada: A History |first=James A. |last=Barclay |authorlink=James A. Barclay |publisher=[[McClelland & Stewart]] |location=Toronto |year=1992 |isbn=978-0-7710-1080-4}}</ref> Jones also received golf lessons from [[Willie Ogg]] when he was in his teenage years.<ref name=\"Ryder Cup\">{{cite book |last=Biddiscombe |first=Ross |title=Ryder Cup Revealed: Tales of the Unexpected |isbn=9780956285010 |publisher=Constant Sports Publishing |location=London, England |date=2014 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=6vrrAwAAQBAJ&pg=PT128&lpg=PT128&dq=Ogg+PGA+of+America#v=onepage&q=Ogg%20PGA%20of%20America&f=false |via=books.Google.com}}</ref> Jones played frequently with his father, a skilled player himself. The younger Jones sometimes battled his own temper on the course, but later controlled his emotions as he became more experienced.<ref name= \"espn\">{{cite news |url=http://espn.go.com/sportscentury/features/00014123.html|title=Bobby Jones was golf's fast study |first=Larry |last=Shwartz |publisher=[[ESPN]] |accessdate=August 25, 2013}}</ref> Jones toured the U.S. during [[World War I]] from 1917 to 1918, playing exhibition matches before large crowds, often with Alexa Stirling and [[Perry Adair]], to generate income for war relief. Playing in front of such crowds in these matches helped him, as he moved into national competition a bit later on.\n\nJones successfully represented the United States for the first time, in two winning international amateur team matches against Canada, in 1919 and 1920, earning three of a possible four points in foursomes and singles play. In 1919 he traveled to [[Hamilton Golf and Country Club]], for his first serious competitive action outside the U.S., while in 1920, [[Engineers Country Club]], in Roslyn, [[Long Island]], hosted the matches. Still a teenager, he was by far the youngest player in the series. Jones also played in the 1919 [[Canadian Open (golf)|Canadian Open]] while in [[Hamilton, Ontario]], performing very well to place tied for second, but 16 shots behind winner [[J. Douglas Edgar]].<ref>Barclay, pp. 298\u20139, 329</ref> Edgar had immigrated from England in 1919 to take a club professional's job in Atlanta at [[Druid Hills Golf Club]]; Edgar mentored and played frequently with Jones from 1919 to 1921. Edgar was credited by Jones with helping develop his game significantly.<ref>''Gone with the Swing'', by Steve Eubanks, excerpted from ''To Win And Die in Dixie'', by Eubanks, ''Sports Illustrated Masters Preview 2010'', April 2010</ref>\n\nJones qualified for his first [[U.S. Open (golf)|U.S. Open]] at age 18 in [[1920 U.S. Open (golf)|1920]], and was paired with the legendary [[Harry Vardon]] for the first two rounds.<ref name=golden>{{cite book |title=Golf's Golden Grind: A History of the PGA Tour |first=Al |last=Barkow |authorlink=Al Barkow |year=1974 |publisher=Burford Books |isbn=978-1580800440}}</ref> He won the [[Southern Amateur]] three times: 1917, 1920, and 1922.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sgagolf.com/ |title=The Southern - A Tradition |publisher=Southern Golf Association |accessdate=September 1, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===First majors===\n\n[[File:Bobby Jones wins British Open in 1930.jpg|thumb|right|210px|British Open win 1930]]\n{{Externalimage\n|align=right\n|width=210px\n|image1=[http://history.library.gatech.edu/items/show/6415 Jones with Grand Slam Trophies]\n}}\nAs an adult, he hit his stride and won his first U.S. Open in [[1923 U.S. Open (golf)|1923]]. From that win at New York's [[Inwood Country Club]], through his 1930 victory in the U.S. Amateur, he won 13 major championships (as they were counted at the time) in 20 attempts.<ref name = \"emperor\">{{cite journal |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1005077/1/index.htm |date=April 11, 1994 |title=The Emperor Jones |first=Ron |last=Fimrite |journal=[[Sports Illustrated]] |accessdate=August 25, 2013}}</ref> Jones was the first player to win The Double, both the U.S. and British Open Championships in the same year (1926). He was the second (and last) to win the U.S. Open and U.S. Amateur in the same year (1930), first accomplished in [[1916 U.S. Open (golf)|1916]] by [[Chick Evans]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wgaesf.org/site/c.dwJTKiO0JgI8G/b.6181219/k.64CB/Chick_Evans_Biography.htm |title=Chick Evans Biography |publisher=[[Western Golf Association]] |accessdate=September 2, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131018030322/http://www.wgaesf.org/site/c.dwJTKiO0JgI8G/b.6181219/k.64CB/Chick_Evans_Biography.htm |archive-date=October 18, 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===1930: Grand Slam===\n\nJones is the only player ever to have won the (pre-Masters) [[Grand Slam (golf)|Grand Slam]], or all four major championships, in the same calendar year (1930). Jones' path to the 1930 Grand Slam title was:\n\n#[[The Amateur Championship]], [[Old Course at St Andrews]], Scotland (May 31, 1930)\n#[[The Open Championship]], [[Royal Liverpool Golf Club]], Hoylake, England (June 20, 1930)\n#[[U.S. Open (golf)|U.S. Open]], [[Interlachen Country Club]], Minnesota (July 12, 1930)\n#[[U.S. Amateur]], [[Merion Golf Club]], Pennsylvania (September 27, 1930<ref>{{cite magazine | url=https://www.si.com/specials/100-greatest/?q=69-the-greatest-year-in-golf | title=The Greatest Year in Golf | magazine=[[Sports Illustrated]] | accessdate=September 25, 2017}}</ref>)\n\nJones made a bet on himself achieving this feat with British bookmakers early in 1930, before the first tournament of the Slam, at odds of 50\u20131, and collected over $60,000 when he did it.<ref name=golfchannel>''The Grand Slam'', television program produced by the [[Golf Channel]], part of \"Classics\" series</ref>\n\nJones represented the United States in the [[Walker Cup]] five times, winning nine of his 10 matches, and the U.S. won the trophy all five times. He served as playing [[Captain (sports)|captain]] of the U.S. team in 1928 and 1930. He also won two other tournaments against professionals: the 1927 Southern Open and the 1930 Southeastern Open. Jones was a lifelong member of the Atlanta Athletic Club (at the club's original site, now the [[East Lake Golf Club]]), and the [[Capital City Club]] in Atlanta.\n\nJones is considered one of the five giants of the 1920s American sports scene, along with baseball's [[Babe Ruth]], [[boxing]]'s [[Jack Dempsey]], [[American football|football]]'s [[Red Grange]], and tennis player [[Bill Tilden]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/sports/longterm/general/povich/launch/grange.htm |title=Grange's Appellation Was No Exaggeration |newspaper=The Washington Post |first=Shirley |last=Povich |accessdate=May 28, 2011 |date=January 29, 1991}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=BrRVY71mDDkC&pg=PA6&lpg=PA6&dq=Ruth+Dempsey+Grange+Tilden+Jones |first=Curt |last=Sampson |title=The Slam: Bobby Jones and the Price of Glory |publisher=Rodale |date=June 19, 2005 |isbn=978-1-59486-120-8 |accessdate=May 28, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.sptimes.com/News/122199/Sports/Bambino_s_curse_begin.shtml |title=Bambino's curse begins as Red Sox trade Ruth |first=Bruce |last=Lowitt |newspaper=[[St. Petersberg Times]] |date=December 21, 1999 |accessdate=May 28, 2011}}</ref> He was the first recipient of the [[Amateur Athletic Union|AAU]]'s [[James E. Sullivan Award|Sullivan Award]] as the top amateur athlete in the United States. He is the only sports figure to receive two [[ticker-tape parade]]s in New York City, the first in 1926 and the second in 1930. Jones is memorialized in [[Augusta, Georgia]], at the Golf Gardens and the [[Bobby Jones Expressway]], also known as [[Interstate 520]], is named after him.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://157.166.226.103/augusta/inaugusta/news/2002/04/08/jones_statue/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131019092355/http://157.166.226.103/augusta/inaugusta/news/2002/04/08/jones_statue/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=October 19, 2013 |title=Jones statue joins golf gardens |newspaper=[[The Augusta Chronicle]] |first=Jason B. |last=Smith |accessdate=September 1, 2013 |date=April 8, 2002 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.interstate-guide.com/i-520_ga.html |title=Interstate 520 Georgia / South Carolina |publisher=Interstate-Guide.com |accessdate=September 1, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Sportsmanship===\n[[File:Bobby Jones c1917.jpg|thumb|upright|left|Bobby Jones circa 1917]]\n\nIn the first round of the [[1925 U.S. Open (golf)|1925 U.S. Open]] at the [[Worcester Country Club]] near Boston, his approach shot to the 11th hole's elevated green fell short into the deep rough of the embankment. As he took his stance to pitch onto the green, the head of his club brushed the grass and caused a slight movement of the ball. He took the shot, then informed his playing partner [[Walter Hagen]] and the [[United States Golf Association|USGA]] official covering their match that he was calling a penalty on himself. Hagen was unable to talk him out of it, and they continued play.  After the round and before he signed his scorecard, officials argued with Jones but he insisted that he had violated Rule 18, moving a ball at rest after address, and took a 77 instead of the 76 he otherwise would have carded. Jones' self-imposed one-stroke penalty eventually cost him the win by a stroke in regulation, necessitating a playoff, which he then lost. Although praised by many sports writers for his gesture, Jones was reported to have said, \"You might as well praise me for not robbing banks.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.golf.com/photos/infamous-golf-rules-violations-blunders/bobby-jones-1925-us-open |title=Infamous Rules Mishaps |work=Golf Magazine |accessdate=August 20, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131017211955/http://www.golf.com/photos/infamous-golf-rules-violations-blunders/bobby-jones-1925-us-open |archivedate=October 17, 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |url=http://harvardmagazine.com/2002/03/bobby-jones.html |title=\"Bobby\" Jones |journal=[[Harvard Magazine]] |first=Craig |last=Lambert |date=March\u2013April 2002 |accessdate=August 20, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://worcestercc.memberstatements.com/tour/tours.cfm?tourid=77762 |title=1925 Men's US Open |publisher=Worcester Country Club |accessdate=August 20, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2008/LIVING/wayoflife/06/12/us.open.history/ |title=Fun and sick facts about U.S. Open |publisher=[[CNN]] |first=Ethan |last=Trex |date=June 12, 2008 |accessdate=August 20, 2013}}</ref>\n\nA similar event occurred in the [[1926 U.S. Open (golf)|next U.S. Open]], played at the [[Scioto Country Club]] in [[Columbus, Ohio]]. In the second round, after his opening round put him in second place, Jones was putting on the 15th green in the face of a strong wind.  After grounding his putter during address to square up the club face, the ball rolled a half turn in the wind when Jones lifted the club head to place it behind the ball.  Although no one else observed this movement of the ball either, again Jones called a penalty on himself, but this time Jones went on to win the tournament, the second of his four U.S. Open victories.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.usopen.com/en_US/champ_experience/pastchamps/1926.html |title=U.S. Open History \u2013 1926 \u2013 Bobby Jones |publisher=USGA |accessdate=August 21, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131018032734/http://www.usopen.com/en_US/champ_experience/pastchamps/1926.html |archivedate=October 18, 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nbcsports.com/node/174366#slide-83 |title=U.S. Open Champions \u2013 1926: Bobby Jones |work=NBC Sports |accessdate=August 21, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe USGA's sportsmanship award is named the [[Bob Jones Award]] in his honor.\n\n===St Andrews, Scotland===\n\nJones had a unique relationship with the town of [[St Andrews]]. On his first appearance on the [[Old Course at St Andrews|Old Course]] in The Open Championship of [[1921 Open Championship|1921]], he withdrew after 11 holes in the third round, when he failed to complete the hole (in effect disqualifying himself), and tore up his scorecard, although he finished the round and indeed played the fourth round as well. He firmly stated his dislike for The Old Course and the town reciprocated, saying in the press, \"Master Bobby is just a boy, and an ordinary boy at that.\" Later, he came to love the Old Course and the town like few others. When he won the Open at the Old Course in [[1927 Open Championship|1927]], he wowed the crowd by asking that the trophy remain with his friends at the [[The Royal and Ancient Golf Club of St Andrews|Royal and Ancient Golf Club]] rather than return with him to Atlanta. He won the [[The Amateur Championship|British Amateur]] over The Old Course in 1930, and scored a [[double eagle (golf)|double eagle]] 2 on the fourth hole (then a par-5, now a par-4), by holing a very long shot from a fairway bunker.<ref name=golfchannel/> In 1958, he was named a [[Freedom of the City|Freeman of the City]] of St Andrews, becoming only the second American to be so honored, the other being [[Benjamin Franklin]] in 1759. As Jones departed Younger Hall with his honor, the assembly spontaneously serenaded him off to the traditional tune of [[Will Ye No Come Back Again?]] in a famously moving tribute.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Wind |first=Herbert Warren |url=https://www.si.com/vault/1958/10/27/560278/will-ye-no-come-back-again |title=Will Ye No' Come Back Again? |date=October 27, 1958 |magazine=[[Sports Illustrated]] |page=33 |accessdate=July 15, 2016}}</ref> Today, a scholarship exchange bearing the Jones name exists between the [[University of St Andrews]] and [[Emory University]], [[Queen's University at Kingston|Queen's University]], [[The University of Western Ontario]] and the [[Georgia Institute of Technology]] in Atlanta. At Emory, four students are sent to St Andrews for an all-expenses-paid year of study and travel. In return, Emory accepts four students from St Andrews each year. The program, the Robert T. Jones Scholarship, is among the most unusual scholarships offered by any university.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.college.emory.edu/program/bobbyjones/scholarships/index.html |title=The Robert T. Jones Jr. Scholarship Program |publisher=Emory University |accessdate=July 24, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===University, family, career===\n\n[[File:Robert Tyre Jones Jr plaque.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Plaque at [[Georgia Tech]] honoring Jones]]\nJones was successful outside of golf. He earned his B.S. in Mechanical Engineering from [[Georgia Institute of Technology|Georgia Tech]] in 1922 and played for the varsity golf team, lettering all four years.<ref name = \"tech\"/><ref>{{cite encyclopedia |url=http://www.georgiaencyclopedia.org/articles/sports-outdoor-recreation/bobby-jones-1902-1971 |title=Bobby Jones (1902\u20131971) |encyclopedia=New Georgia Encyclopedia |accessdate=August 21, 2013}}</ref> Jones was a member of the [[Sigma Alpha Epsilon]] [[Fraternities and sororities in North America|fraternity]], and the Georgia Phi chapter house at Georgia Tech is named in his honor.\n\nHe then earned an A.B. in English Literature from [[Harvard College]] in 1924, where he was a member of the [[Owl Club (Harvard)|Owl Club]]. In 1926 he entered [[Emory University School of Law]] and became a member of [[Phi Delta Phi]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oaklandcemetery.com/projects/bobbyjones/|title=Bobby Jones \"Getaway\"|publisher=Historic Oakland Foundation|accessdate=December 5, 2017}}</ref> After only three semesters he passed the Georgia [[bar exam]] and subsequently joined his father's law firm, Jones, Evins, Moore and Howell, (predecessor to [[Alston & Bird]]), in Atlanta, Georgia.<ref name = \"emperor\"/>\n\nJones married Mary Rice Malone in 1924, whom he met in 1919 while a freshman at Georgia Tech. They had three children: Clara Malone (1925<!--April 18, 1925-->\u20131994<!--February 10, 1994-->),<ref name=cjbfgr>{{cite web|url=https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/39024145 |publisher=Find A Grave |title=Clara Jones Black |accessdate=April 18, 2014}}{{Primary source inline|date=March 2020}}</ref> Robert Tyre III (<!--Dec 13-->1926\u2013<!--Dec 20-->1973), and Mary Ellen (b. <!--Jan 29-->1931).<ref name=bjiprofth>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=ra1RAAAAIBAJ&sjid=wiEEAAAAIBAJ&pg=4224%2C3639951 |newspaper=Milwaukee Journal |agency=Associated Press photo |title=Bobby Jones is proud of these |date=July 9, 1929 |page=green sheet }}</ref><ref name=thrldch>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=FN1PAAAAIBAJ&sjid=jVQDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6230%2C3234206|newspaper=Evening Independent |agency=Associated Press |title=Bobby Jones' children thrilled as famous father makes debut as golf speaker on radio chain |date=January 15, 1931 |page=11 }}</ref><ref name=loilln>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2506&dat=19711219&id=cdReAAAAIBAJ&sjid=tlENAAAAIBAJ&pg=746,4364859 |newspaper=News and Courier |location=Charleston, SC |agency=Associated Press |title=Bobby Jones dies after long illness |date=December 19, 1971 |page=2B }}</ref><ref name=bjhand>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=B-00AAAAIBAJ&sjid=hOgDAAAAIBAJ&pg=2834%2C1968280 |newspaper=Eugene Register-Guard |agency=Associated Press |title=Bobby Jones has a new daughter |date=January 29, 1931|page=10 }}</ref>\n\nWhen he retired from golf at age 28, he concentrated on his Atlanta law practice.<ref name =\"master\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/learning/general/onthisday/bday/0317.html |title=Bobby Jones, Golf Master, Dies; Only Player to Win Grand Slam |newspaper=The New York Times |first=Frank |last=Litsky |date=December 19, 1971 |accessdate=September 1, 2013}}</ref> That same year, 1930, he was honored with the first [[James E. Sullivan Award]], awarded annually by the [[Amateur Athletic Union]] (AAU) to the most outstanding amateur athlete in the United States.\n\n===Golf films, golf club design===\n\nJones made 18 instructional golf films in Hollywood between 1931 and 1933 in which he coached well-known film stars on golf. The films were popular, and Jones gave up his amateur status while earning lucrative contract money for this venture. These films were put into storage and were unavailable for decades, but a surviving print was located 60 years later and put into video format for preservation by [[Ely Callaway]], a distant cousin of Jones's.\n\nIn the early 1930s Jones worked with J Victor East (an Australian) of [[Spalding (sports equipment)|A.G. Spalding & Co.]] to develop the first set of matched steel-shafted clubs; the clubs sold very well and are still considered among the best-designed sets ever made.<ref name=golden/>\n\n===Augusta National Golf Club===\n[[File:1933 Goudey Sport Kings 38 Bobby Jones.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Jones in 1933]]\nFollowing his retirement from competitive golf in 1930, and even in the years leading up to that, Jones had become one of the most famous sports figures in the world, and was recognized virtually everywhere he went in public. While certainly appreciative of the enormous adulation and media coverage, this massive attention caused Jones to lose personal privacy in golf circles, and he wished to create a private golf club where he and his friends could play golf in peace and quiet. For several years, he searched for a property near Atlanta where he could develop his own golf club. His friend [[Clifford Roberts]], a New York City investment dealer, knew of Jones's desire, became aware of a promising property for sale in Augusta, Georgia, where Jones's mother-in-law<ref>{{cite web|url=http://chronicle.augusta.com/content/blog-post/don-rhodes/2010-04-05/bobby-jones-had-augusta-relatives|title=The Augusta Chronicle: Local & World News, Sports & Entertainment in Augusta, GA|website=The Augusta Chronicle}}</ref> had grown up, and informed Jones about it.<ref name=making>{{cite book |title=The Making of the Masters: Clifford Roberts, Augusta National, and Golf's Most Prestigious Tournament |first=David |last=Owen |publisher=Simon & Schuster |date=April 2, 2003 |isbn=0-684-86751-6}}</ref> Jones first visited Fruitlands, an Augusta [[arboretum]] and [[Indigo dye|indigo]] plantation since the Civil War era, in the spring of 1930,<ref name=golfchannel/> and he purchased it for $70,000 in 1931, with the plan to design a golf course on the site.<ref>{{cite book |title=Arnie & Jack: Palmer, Nicklaus, and Golf's Greatest Rivalry |first=Ian |last=O'Connor |year=2008 |publisher=Houghton Mifflin |isbn=978-0-618-75446-5 |url=https://archive.org/details/arniejackpalmern00ocon }}</ref>\n\nJones co-designed the Augusta National course with [[Alister MacKenzie]]; the new club opened in early 1933. He founded the Masters Tournament, first played at Augusta in March 1934. The new tournament, originally known as the Augusta National Invitational, was an immediate success, and attracted most of the world's top players right from its start. Jones came out of retirement to play, essentially on an exhibition basis, and his presence guaranteed enormous media attention, boosting the new tournament's fame.<ref name=making/>\n\nDuring [[World War II]], Jones served as an officer in the [[U.S. Army Air Corps]]. His superiors wanted him to play exhibition golf in the United States, but Jones was insistent on serving overseas. In 1943 he was promoted to major and trained as an intelligence officer, serving in England with the 84th Fighter Wing, which was part of the [[Ninth Air Force]]. While in England, he made the acquaintance of General [[Dwight D. Eisenhower]]. Landing in [[Invasion of Normandy|Normandy]] on June 7, 1944, Jones spent two months with a front line division as a [[prisoner of war]] interrogator, reaching the rank of [[lieutenant colonel]].<ref>{{cite book |first=Mark |last=Frost |authorlink=Mark Frost |title=The Grand Slam: Bobby Jones, America, and the Story of Golf |year=2004 |publisher=Hyperion Books |location=New York |isbn=978-1-4013-0751-6 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/grandslamthe00mark/page/458 458\u20139] |url=https://archive.org/details/grandslamthe00mark/page/458 }}</ref> During the war, Jones permitted the [[U.S. Army]] to graze cattle on the grounds at Augusta National. Later, in 1947, he founded Peachtree Golf Club in Atlanta and co-designed the course with [[Robert Trent Jones]].\n\nIn 1966, the governing board and membership of Augusta National passed a resolution naming Jones President in Perpetuity.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.masters.com/en_US/tournament/founders.html|title=About the Masters \u2013 The Founders |publisher=masters.com |accessdate=September 2, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Masters Tournament, health worries===\n[[File:BobbyJones-grave-1.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Jones' grave in Atlanta's [[Oakland Cemetery (Atlanta)|Oakland Cemetery]], with putting green, golf balls, and mementos.]]\n\nJones played in the first dozen Masters, through [[1948 Masters Tournament|1948]], but only in the first as a competitor. By then, his health at age 46 had declined to the stage where this was no longer possible. With his health difficulties, being past his prime, and not competing elsewhere to stay in tournament form, he never truly contended at the Masters, although his scores were usually respectable. These were almost all ceremonial performances, since his main duty was as host of the event. His extraordinary popularity, efforts with the course design, and tournament organization boosted the profile of the Masters significantly. The tournament, jointly run by Jones and Clifford Roberts, made many important innovations which became the norm elsewhere, such as gallery ropes to control the flow of the large crowds, many scoreboards around the course, the use of red / green numbers on those scoreboards to denote under / over par scores, an international field of top players, high-caliber television coverage, and week-long admission passes for patrons, which became extremely hard to obtain. The tournament also sought and welcomed feedback from players, fans, and writers, leading to continual improvement over the years. The Masters gradually evolved to being one of the most respected tournaments in the world, one of the four major championships.<ref name=making/>\n\n===Incapacity and death===\n\nIn 1948, Jones was diagnosed with [[syringomyelia]], a fluid-filled cavity in the spinal cord that causes crippling pain, then paralysis; he was eventually restricted to a wheelchair. He died in Atlanta on December 18, 1971, three days after converting to [[Catholic Church|Catholicism]].<ref name=loilln/> Jones was baptized on his deathbed by Monsignor John D. Stapleton, pastor of the [[Cathedral of Christ the King (Atlanta)|Cathedral of Christ the King]] in Atlanta, and attended by the Jones family<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1755&dat=19711219&id=ZuIbAAAAIBAJ&sjid=eWYEAAAAIBAJ&pg=6942,1219561&hl=en |title=Golfing Great Bobby Jones Dies |agency=[[Associated Press]] |newspaper=[[Sarasota Herald-Tribune]] |location=Florida |date=December 19, 1971 |page=1-C,4-C |accessdate=December 20, 2015}}</ref> was buried in Atlanta's historic [[Oakland Cemetery (Atlanta)|Oakland Cemetery]]. Jones was inducted into the [[World Golf Hall of Fame]] in 1974.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.worldgolfhalloffame.org/bobby-jones/ |title=Bobby Jones |publisher=[[World Golf Hall of Fame]] |accessdate=May 28, 2011}}</ref>\n\nHis widow Mary died less than four years later in 1975 at age 72, following the death of their son, Robert T. Jones III, of a heart attack in 1973 <!--Dec 20--> at age 47.<ref name=sobjds73>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=ylosAAAAIBAJ&sjid=Nc0EAAAAIBAJ&pg=1359%2C4847954 |newspaper=Spartanburg (SC) Herald-Journal |agency=Associated Press |title=Son of famous golfer Jones dies |date=December 22, 1973 |page=B2 }}</ref> Daughter Clara died in 1994 <!--Mrs. Black, Feb 10-->at age 68.<ref name=cjbfgr/>\n\n==Tournament wins (34) ==\n*1908 East Lake Children's Tournament\n*1911 Junior Championship Cup of the Atlanta Athletic Club\n*1915 Invitation Tournament at Roebuck Springs, Birmingham Country Club Invitation, Davis & Freeman Cup at East Lake, East Lake Club Championship, Druid Hills Club Championship\n*1916 Georgia Amateur, Birmingham Country Club Invitation, Cherokee Club Invitation, East Lake Invitational\n*1917 [[Southern Amateur]]\n*1919 Yates-Gode Tournament\n*1920 Davis & Freeman Cup at East Lake, [[Southern Amateur]], Morris County Invitational\n*1922 [[Southern Amateur]]\n*1923 '''[[U.S. Open (golf)|U.S. Open]]'''\n*1924 '''[[U.S. Amateur]]'''\n*1925 '''[[U.S. Amateur]]'''\n*1926 '''[[The Open Championship]]''', '''[[U.S. Open (golf)|U.S. Open]]'''\n*1927 Southern Open, '''[[The Open Championship]]''', '''[[U.S. Amateur]]'''\n*1928 Warren K. Wood Memorial, '''[[U.S. Amateur]]'''\n*1929 '''[[U.S. Open (golf)|U.S. Open]]''' \n*1930 Southeastern Open, [[Golf Illustrated Gold Vase]], '''[[The Amateur Championship]]''', '''[[The Open Championship]]''', '''[[U.S. Open (golf)|U.S. Open]]''', '''[[U.S. Amateur]]'''\n\nOpen and amateur-only [[men's major golf championships|majors]] shown in '''bold'''.\n\n==Major championships==\n\n===Wins (13)===\n\n====The Opens (7)====\n{|class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n!Year!!Championship!!54 holes!!Winning score!!Margin!!Runner(s)-up\n|- style=\"background:#fbceb1;\"\n| align=center|[[1923 U.S. Open (golf)|1923]] ||[[U.S. Open (golf)|U.S. Open]] ||3 shot lead ||align=right|+8 (71\u201373\u201376\u201376=296) ||Playoff <sup>1</sup> ||{{Flagicon|SCO}} [[Bobby Cruickshank]]\n|- style=\"background:#abcdef;\"\n| align=center|[[1926 Open Championship|1926]] ||[[The Open Championship]] ||2 shot deficit ||align=right|(72\u201372\u201373\u201374=291) ||2 strokes ||{{Flagicon|USA}} [[Al Watrous]]\n|- style=\"background:#fbceb1;\"\n| align=center|[[1926 U.S. Open (golf)|1926]] || U.S. Open ||3 shot deficit ||align=right|+5 (70\u201379\u201371\u201373=293) ||1 stroke ||{{Flagicon|USA}} [[Joe Turnesa]]\n|- style=\"background:#abcdef;\"\n| align=center|[[1927 Open Championship|1927]] || The Open Championship ||4 shot lead ||align=right|(68\u201372\u201373\u201372=285) ||6 strokes ||{{Flagicon|Jersey}} [[Aubrey Boomer]], {{Flagicon|ENG}} [[Fred Robson]]\n|- style=\"background:#fbceb1;\"\n| align=center|[[1929 U.S. Open (golf)|1929]] || U.S. Open (golf)|U.S. Open ||3 shot lead ||align=right|+6 (69\u201375\u201371\u201379=294) ||Playoff <sup>2</sup> ||{{Flagicon|USA}} [[Al Espinosa]]\n|- style=\"background:#abcdef;\"\n| align=center|[[1930 Open Championship|1930]] || The Open Championship||1 shot deficit ||align=right|(70\u201372\u201374\u201375=291) ||2 strokes ||{{Flagicon|USA}} [[Leo Diegel]], {{Flagicon|SCO}} [[Macdonald Smith]]\n|- style=\"background:#fbceb1;\"\n| align=center|[[1930 U.S. Open (golf)|1930]] || U.S. Open ||5 shot lead ||align=right|\u22121 (71\u201373\u201368\u201375=287) ||2 strokes ||{{Flagicon|SCO}} Macdonald Smith\n|}\n<sup>1</sup> Defeated Bobby Cruickshank in an 18-hole playoff: Jones 76 (+4), Cruickshank 78 (+6). <br/>\n<sup>2</sup> Defeated Al Espinosa in a 36-hole playoff: Jones 72\u201369=141 (\u22123), Espinosa 84\u201380=164 (+20).\n\n====The Amateurs (6)====\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year!!Championship!!Winning score!!Runner-up\n|-\n| 1924 || [[U.S. Amateur]] || align=center|9 & 8 || {{Flagicon|USA}} [[George Von Elm]]\n|-\n| 1925 || U.S. Amateur || align=center|8 & 7 || {{Flagicon|USA}} [[Watts Gunn]]\n|-\n| 1927 || U.S. Amateur || align=center|8 & 7 || {{Flagicon|USA}} [[Chick Evans]]\n|-\n| 1928 || U.S. Amateur || align=center|10 & 9 || {{Flagicon|ENG}} [[Philip Perkins]]\n|-\n| 1930 || [[The Amateur Championship]] || align=center|7 & 6 || {{Flagicon|ENG}} [[Roger Wethered]]\n|-\n| 1930 || U.S. Amateur || align=center|8 & 7 || {{Flagicon|USA}} [[Eugene V. Homans]]\n|}\n\nNational Amateur championships were counted as majors at the time. Jones' actual major total using the standard in place in his lifetime was 13.\n\n===Results timeline===\nThe majors of Jones' time (those for which as an amateur he was eligible) were the U.S. and British Opens and Amateurs.\n\n{| cellpadding=\"3\" cellspacing=\"0\" border=\"1\" style=\"font-size: 95%; border: #aaa solid 1px; border-collapse: collapse;text-align:center;\"\n|- style=\"background:#eee;\"\n!Tournament!!1916!!1917!!1918!!1919!!1920!!1921!!1922!!1923!!1924!!1925!!1926!!1927!!1928!!1929!!1930\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[U.S. Open (golf)|U.S. Open]]\n|style=\"background:#eeeeee;\"|\n|style=\"background:#eeeeee;\"|NT\n|style=\"background:#eeeeee;\"|NT\n|style=\"background:#eeeeee;\"|\n|style=\"background:yellow;\"|T8\n|style=\"background:yellow;\"|T5\n|style=\"background:yellow;\"|T2 <span style=\"font-size:87%;\">LA</span>\n|style=\"background:lime;\"|'''1''' <span style=\"font-size:87%;\">LA</span>\n|style=\"background:yellow;\"|2 <span style=\"font-size:87%;\">LA</span>\n|style=\"background:yellow;\"|2 <span style=\"font-size:87%;\">LA</span>\n|style=\"background:lime;\"|'''1''' <span style=\"font-size:87%;\">LA</span>\n|T11 <span style=\"font-size:87%;\">LA</span>\n|style=\"background:yellow;\"|2 <span style=\"font-size:87%;\">LA</span>\n|style=\"background:lime;\"|'''1''' <span style=\"font-size:87%;\">LA</span>\n|style=\"background:lime;\"|'''1''' <span style=\"font-size:87%;\">LA</span>\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[The Open Championship]]\n|style=\"background:#eeeeee;\"|NT\n|style=\"background:#eee